'''Cheryl H. Arrowsmith''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] structural biologist and is the Chief Scientist at the Toronto laboratory of the [[Structural Genomics Consortium]]. Her contributions to protein structural biology<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uhnresearch.ca/researchers/profile.php?lookup=210 |title=Cheryl H. Arrowsmith |publisher=uhnresearch.ca |accessdate=December 27, 2017}}</ref> includes the use of [[protein NMR|NMR]] and [[X-ray crystallography]] to pursue structures of proteins on a proteome wide scale.
She received her [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in chemistry at the [[University of Toronto]] in 1987 and post-doctoral training at [[Stanford University]] working with Professor [[Oleg Jardetzky]]. One of her areas of interest is the tumour suppressor [[p53]] and related proteins.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nmr.uhnres.utoronto.ca/arrowsmith/ |title=Cheryl Arrowsmith |publisher=utoronto.ca |accessdate=December 27, 2017}}</ref>
Her current research is to determine the [[Protein Structure|3-dimensional structures]] of human proteins of therapeutic relevance by [[structural proteomics]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Chandonia JM, Brenner SE |title=The impact of structural genomics: expectations and outcomes |journal=Science |volume=311 |issue=5759 |pages=347–51 |date=January 2006 |pmid=16424331 |doi=10.1126/science.1121018 |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/311/5759/347}}</ref> She made significant contributions to [[Epigenetics|epigenetic]] signaling with her highest cited paper is "Epigenetic protein families: a new frontier for drug discovery"<ref>Cheryl H. Arrowsmith, Chas Bountra, Paul V. Fish, Kevin Lee & Matthieu Schapira. Epigenetic protein families: a new frontier for drug discovery. Nature Reviews Drug Discovery 11, 384–400 (2012)</ref> cited at 802 times, according to Google Scholar.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=0%2C44&q=Cheryl+Arrowsmith&btnG= |title=Cheryl Arrowsmith |publisher=scholar.google.com |accessdate=December 27, 2017}}</ref>
Arrowsmith was named a Fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] (AAAS) in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://medicine.utoronto.ca/news/arrowsmith-named-aaas-fellow |title=Arrowsmith named AAAS Fellow |publisher=utoronto.ca |accessdate=December 27, 2017}}</ref>
