{{Infobox Podcast | title = Grammar Girl's Quick and Dirty Tips for Better Writing | image = | caption = | host = [[Mignon Fogarty]] | picture format = | url = {{URL|http://grammar.quickanddirtytips.com}} | rss = http://www.qdnow.com/grammar.xml | atom = | status = | began = July 30, 2006 | ended = | genre = | ratings = }}
'''''Grammar Girl's Quick and Dirty Tips for Better Writing''''' is an educational [[podcast]] produced by [[Mignon Fogarty]] that was launched in July 2006 and the title of a print book by Fogarty that was released in July 2008. The podcast, which has ranked as high as #2 on iTunes,<ref name="cnn">{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/TECH/internet/01/22/grammar.girl/index.html | title='Grammar Girl' a quick and dirty success | work=CNN.com | author=Williams, David E. | date=January 25, 2007 | accessdate=2008-07-24}}</ref> offers short one-topic English [[grammar]] lessons at no charge to subscribers hoping to improve their writing skills.
The print book offers advice similar to that found in the podcast and reached number nine on the New York Times best-seller list for paperback advice books.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/17/books/bestseller/bestpaperadvice.html?_r=1&oref=login | title=Best Sellers | work=August 17, 2008 New York Times | accessdate=2008-08-20 | date=August 17, 2008}}</ref>
==Listenership==
The Grammar Girl podcast had been downloaded over seven million times by December 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0805088318 | title=Product Description | work=Amazon.com, Grammar Girl's Quick and Dirty Tips for Better Writing | accessdate=2008-08-20}}</ref> According to a Podtrac survey conducted in October 2006, approximately 50% of listeners are male and the other 50% are female. Listeners are encouraged to submit grammar questions by e-mail and voicemail. The majority of episodes are built around these submissions.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}
==Recognition== The podcast has won three awards: the 2007 [[Podcast Awards|Podcast Award]] for Best Education Podcast,<ref name="podcast awards">{{cite web | url=http://podcastawards.com/ | title=Podcast Awards | accessdate=2008-07-24}}</ref> the 2007 Podcast Peer Award for Favorite Audio Program, and the 2006 Podcast Peer Award for Best Education Podcast.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ilonlineconf.org/index.cfm?page=featured_speakers | title=Featured Speakers | work=2008 Illinois Online Conference for Teaching and Learning | accessdate=2008-07-24}}</ref>
The Grammar Girl podcast was the subject of an article in the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' (November 4–5, 2006), recommended by the German newspaper [http://www.bild.t-online.de/BTO/tipps-trends/digital-leben/aktuell/2006/11/sprachkurse-ipod/ar-sprachkurse-ipod.html Bild.de] (December 1, 2006), profiled on [http://www.cnn.com/2007/TECH/internet/01/22/grammar.girl/index.html CNN.com] (January 23, 2007), and positively reviewed by the [http://www.podcastingtricks.com/2006/11/30/favorite-podcasts-grammar-girl-podcastingtrickscom/ Podcasting Tricks] website (November 30, 2006).{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}
In their end-of-year review, iTunes staff listed the Grammar Girl podcast as a favorite for 2006.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} The show was also listed as an iTunes People's Choice podcast for 2006, ranking 29th in number of new subscribers for the year.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} In 2013, iTunes listed Grammar Girl as one of 12 "Best Classic Podcasts". <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slashgear.com/itunes-and-app-store-best-of-2013-17309055/ | title=iTunes and App Store Best of 2013 | accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref>
Mignon Fogarty appeared on the March 26, 2007 episode of ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' as a grammar expert.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.oprah.com/slideshow/oprahshow/oprahshow1_ss_20070326/6 | title=Letter to Oprah | work=2007 Oprah Winfrey Show | accessdate=2008-08-20}}</ref> She was on the show to answer a viewer question about the use of possessive apostrophes. The viewer thought a previous show should have been titled "Oprah's and Gayle's Big Adventure", but Fogarty confirmed that "Oprah and Gayle's Big Adventure" was a correct use of compound possession. She went on to discuss several other common grammar errors, including "affect vs. effect" and "who vs. whom".
The Grammar Girl print book reached number nine on the August 17, 2008 New York Times best-seller list for paperback advice books.
